They are a 12-time Olympic medallist (eight gold, four silver) and the seven-time defending Olympic 4x400m relay champions (1996-2020), having won consecutive golds since Atlanta 1996. Since the inception of the world championships in 1983, when they were not on the podium, the United States has since gone on to become a fifteen-time 4x400m relay medallist (10 gold, four silver, one bronze). The longest run of back-to-back gold medals was at four consecutive world championships (2007, 2009, 2011, 2013), with another run of three global titles starting in 2017. The United States owns the top four fastest 4x400m relay times in world championship history, led by the quartet of Gwen Torrence, Maicel Malone, Natasha Kaiser-Brown, and Jearl Miles Clark in 1993 with a time of 3:16.71.

They qualified for the 2024 Olympic Games at the 2024 World Relay Championships in Nassau, Bahamas, after finishing top two in their heat.

The Japanese women's team competed in all four Olympic Games that featured the team event. Their debut was in Beijing 2008, when they lost to the Republic of Korea 3-1 in the bronze medal match. In London 2012, they took silver after reaching the final and losing 3-0 to the People’s Republic of China. At the world championships, between 2001 and 2024 Japan only failed to win a medal at one edition of the tournament, in 2012. They were runners-up at five consecutive editions from 2014 to 2024, losing the final to the Chinese team on all five occasions, and claimed bronze at five editions from 2001 to 2010. In the mid-20th century, Japan was a global powerhouse, winning eight world titles from 1952 to 1971.

At the Asian Championships, Japan finished on the podium at ten out of eleven editions of the tournament from 2003 to 2023, and won one gold, in 2021, when the People’s Republic of China did not compete to focus on the 2021 National Games of China as well as travel and quarantine restrictions as a result of the Covid-19 pandemic. They won three consecutive Asian Games gold medals from 1958 to 1966, and returned to the podium recently, in 2022, when they claimed silver after losing the final 3-0 against the Chinese.

Japan qualified for the 2024 Olympic Games as a quarter-finalist at the World Team Table Tennis Championships.

At the world championships, Canada is a six-time medallist, winning three gold (1995, 1997, 2022) and three bronze (1993, 2013, 2015).

The Swedish men's team has competed in all four Olympic Games that featured the team event. Their debut was in Beijing 2008, when they didn't pass the group stage. In London 2012, they were eliminated in the first round after a 3-1 loss to Germany. In Rio 2016, they reached the quarterfinals but lost to the Republic of Korea 3-1, the same phase they reached in Tokyo 2020, when they were eliminated after a 3-1 loss to Japan.

Once a global powerhouse, Sweden's star has faded in the 21st century. As of 2024, Sweden remains the only team since Hungary in 1979 to have disrupted the People’s Republic of China's team dominance at the world championships, claiming four titles between 1989 and 2000. But after taking home bronze in 2001, Sweden failed to win a medal at the next nine editions of the tournament.

However, they showed signs of resurgence on home soil in 2018 when they reached the semifinals for the first time since 2004, where they were beaten by the all-conquering Chinese team. At the 2022 edition, they reached the quarterfinals but lost 3-0 to the People’s Republic of China. In 2024, they reached the Round of 16 but lost to Chinese Taipei 3-2.

At the continental level, in recent years the Swedish team have hinted at a potential return to former glory. They were beaten by Portugal in the semifinals at the 2019 European Championships. After that, they reached the quarterfinals in 2022 but lost 3-0 to China. In 2024, they reached the Round of 16 and were eliminated by Chinese Taipei after losing 3-2. Sweden last won the European championship gold in 2002, which was their 14th title at the tournament since 1964.

They qualified for the 2024 Olympic Games at the Europe continental qualification event.
